don't want to work in the gaming industry anymore, wrote a paper once about it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Well anyway I don't want to discourage you, but I think you should know that it's not just fun and games there <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Remember that for every Carmack and Sid Meier, Peter Molyneux and Chris Roberts there are hundreds of guys who couldn't keep up, got burned out or just withered away. Of course if you are a texture artist it might be easier, dunno, I can only code. Or check that Tommy Tallarico guy who only does sound and music from his home studio and has that Tv show, I think it's called Electric Playground. I imagine working only on that aspect at home can be rather relaxing and he has quite a nice sum of cashola. Well anyway the only thing I would work in that segment of the industry is coding tools for mappers/artists/modellers. Good luck and start trolling some gaming messageboards, www.lionhead.com/boards had a good one and www.developium.com was a promising forum. Haven't bothered to contribute or even read any lately, so not sure where to start, but you could hook up with some folks on the net and work on some game online, see what you feel like doing, what you good at and how much planning a game needs before even you start it. <p><font size=-3>[Worthless Class] Rezilaturb (Tubby Bitch)<br>
